SIZECONTEMO

Antonio Schettino

2017-03-09

In this project we will investigate the electrophysiological correlates of the combined processing of basic visual properties (i.e., size and contrast) and the emotional content of simple words.

# setup report output
options(width=120,scipen=999,digits=3) # change output width (for better printing), disable scientific notation (default: scipen=0), constrain output to 4 decimals
opts_chunk$set(warning=FALSE,message=FALSE,fig.width=10,fig.height=6) # for each chunk, display the output but not the R code (echo=FALSE), no package warnings (message=FALSE), no package messages (message=FALSE), width and height of all figures
data.EEG.trial.all <- read.csv(paste(expphase,"_trialEEG.csv",sep=""),header=TRUE) # load data

data.EEG.trial <- data.EEG.trial.all[data.EEG.trial.all$bin %in% c(1:8),] # subset trials main experiment

data.EEG.trial$size <- revalue(factor(data.EEG.trial$bin),c("1"="large","2"="small","3"="large","4"="small","5"="large","6"="small","7"="large","8"="small")) # main effect of size

data.EEG.trial$cont <- revalue(factor(data.EEG.trial$bin),c("1"="dark","2"="dark","3"="bright","4"="bright","5"="dark","6"="dark","7"="bright","8"="bright")) # main effect of contrast

data.EEG.trial$emo <- revalue(factor(data.EEG.trial$bin),c("1"="negative","2"="negative","3"="negative","4"="negative","5"="neutral","6"="neutral","7"="neutral","8"="neutral")) # main effect of emotion

data.EEG.trial$bin <- revalue(factor(data.EEG.trial$bin),c("1"="negativeLargeDark","2"="negativeSmallDark","3"="negativeLargeBright","4"="negativeSmallBright","5"="neutralLargeDark","6"="neutralSmallDark","7"="neutralLargeBright","8"="neutralSmallBright")) # recode bin variable

data.EEG.trial <- within(data.EEG.trial,size<-relevel(size,ref="large")) # reference size to large
data.EEG.trial <- within(data.EEG.trial,cont<-relevel(cont,ref="dark")) # reference cont to dark
data.EEG.trial <- within(data.EEG.trial,emo<-relevel(emo,ref="neutral")) # reference emo to neutral

The data we will use in this demo come from a pilot experiment (N=9).

We will first focus on the ERP data of the main task.

MAIN TASK 

# assess normality
ERPcomp <- factor(c("P1","N1","EPN","LPP")) # ERP components

for(i in levels(ERPcomp)) { # loop through components
  for(j in levels(data.EEG.trial$bin)) { # loop through conditions
    tempdata <- data.EEG.trial[data.EEG.trial$bin==j,i] # subset current condition and ERP
    
    jpeg(filename=paste(wd,"graphs/main/",i,"/",j,".jpg",sep=""),width=480,height=480,units="px",quality=100) # save as jpeg
    plotdist(tempdata,histo=TRUE,demp=TRUE) # empirical density and cumulative distribution
    dev.off()
  }
}

Density plots (not shown in the output) suggest that the normal distribution is a parsimonious approximate description of the data.

We will use linear mixed-effects models with random intercepts and fixed slopes. Models with random slopes have troubles converging, particularly on small datasets. The random factor is participants, although in the future we will include items (i.e., the individual words) as well.

We will compute the following models:

  1. null model
  2. main effect of size
  3. main effect of contrast
  4. main effect of emotion
  5. main effects of size and contrast
  6. main effects of size and emotion
  7. main effects of contrast and emotion
  8. main effects of size, contrast, and emotion
  9. size x contrast interaction
  10. size x emotion interaction
  11. contrast x emotion interaction
  12. size x contrast x emotion interaction

We will then compare them all using the Bayesian Infomation Criterion (BIC).

### null model

# P1.sizecontemo.lmer.fixedslope.contr$contrasts

### model comparison via Bayesian Infomation Criterion (BIC)
P1.lmer.fixedslope.BIC <- BIC(P1.null.lmer.fixedslope,P1.size.lmer.fixedslope,P1.cont.lmer.fixedslope,P1.emo.lmer.fixedslope,P1.sizecontmaineff.lmer.fixedslope,P1.sizeemomaineff.lmer.fixedslope,P1.contemomaineff.lmer.fixedslope,P1.allmaineff.lmer.fixedslope,P1.sizecont.lmer.fixedslope,P1.sizeemo.lmer.fixedslope,P1.contemo.lmer.fixedslope,P1.sizecontemo.lmer.fixedslope)

# summary
compare.P1.lmer.fixedslope <- data.frame(model=c("null","size","contrast","emotion","size+contrast","size+emotion","contrast+emotion","size+contrast+emotion","size*contrast","size*emotion","contrast*emotion","size*contrast*emotion"),BIC=P1.lmer.fixedslope.BIC$BIC)
compare.P1.lmer.fixedslope <- compare.P1.lmer.fixedslope[with(compare.P1.lmer.fixedslope,order(BIC)),] # sort according to BIC (in ascending order)
compare.P1.lmer.fixedslope

SIZE LOCALIZER 

data.EEG.trial.SizeLoc <- data.EEG.trial.all[data.EEG.trial.all$bin %in% c(9:11),] # subset trials size localizer

data.EEG.trial.SizeLoc$bin <- revalue(factor(data.EEG.trial.SizeLoc$bin),c("9"="LocSmall","10"="LocMid","11"="LocLarge")) # recode bin variable

data.EEG.trial.SizeLoc <- within(data.EEG.trial.SizeLoc,bin<-relevel(bin,ref="LocMid")) # reference size to mid
# assess normality
ERPcomp <- factor(c("P1","N1","EPN","LPP")) # ERP components

for(i in levels(ERPcomp)) { # loop through components
  for(j in levels(data.EEG.trial.SizeLoc$bin)) { # loop through conditions
    tempdata <- data.EEG.trial.SizeLoc[data.EEG.trial.SizeLoc$bin==j,i] # subset current condition and ERP
    
    jpeg(filename=paste(wd,"graphs/SizeLoc/",i,"/",j,".jpg",sep=""),width=480,height=480,units="px",quality=100) # save as jpeg
    plotdist(tempdata,histo=TRUE,demp=TRUE) # empirical density and cumulative distribution
    dev.off()
  }
}

Density plots (not shown in the output) suggest that the normal distribution is a parsimonious approximate description of the data. Therefore, linear mixed-effects models are appropriate (see above).

CONTRAST LOCALIZER 

data.EEG.trial.ContLoc <- data.EEG.trial.all[data.EEG.trial.all$bin %in% c(12:14),] # subset trials contrast localizer

data.EEG.trial.ContLoc$bin <- revalue(factor(data.EEG.trial.ContLoc$bin),c("12"="LowCon","13"="MidCon","14"="HighCon")) # recode bin variable

data.EEG.trial.ContLoc <- within(data.EEG.trial.ContLoc,bin<-relevel(bin,ref="MidCon")) # reference contrast to mid
# assess normality
ERPcomp <- factor(c("P1","N1","EPN","LPP")) # ERP components

for(i in levels(ERPcomp)) { # loop through components
  for(j in levels(data.EEG.trial.ContLoc$bin)) { # loop through conditions
    tempdata <- data.EEG.trial.ContLoc[data.EEG.trial.ContLoc$bin==j,i] # subset current condition and ERP
    
    jpeg(filename=paste(wd,"graphs/ContLoc/",i,"/",j,".jpg",sep=""),width=480,height=480,units="px",quality=100) # save as jpeg
    plotdist(tempdata,histo=TRUE,demp=TRUE) # empirical density and cumulative distribution
    dev.off()
  }
}

Density plots (not shown in the output) suggest that the normal distribution is a parsimonious approximate description of the data. Therefore, linear mixed-effects models are appropriate (see above).
